won’t know what’s going on in class and you can’t be meaningfully involved.

Professor’s questions, asking your own questions, commenting upon the

Participation in this manner matters in this class. The Professor will conduct class using the

**3. CORE AND PATHWAYS**  
**_This course is approved for inclusion in the Ethics Core and in the following Core  
Pathways: Applied Ethics; Democracy; Human Rights in a Global World; and Law &  
Justice._**

4.1 Weighting.** First paper: 20%; second paper: 25%; final exam: 35%; reading quizzes:  
20%.  
**4.2 Final grade determination.** The Professor gives an all things considered final grade to  
students. He takes into account the quality of a student’s fulfillment of the course requirements  
(especially the written assignments), participation, attendance, performance on reading quizzes,  
effort, attitude toward critical thinking and learning, and improvement (or lack thereof) over the  
course

**4.3 Grade monitoring.** This is primarily the student’s responsibility. See #6 in the section  
below. Note: the Professor does _not_ post any grades on Camino. If you want to know how you

are doing on the reading quizzes, take responsibility for yourself, and ask the Professor.

    apparently enhances memory through the movements — muscle memory, as it were.

**5.3 Academic integrity**. As a result of a student led initiative, Santa Clara University is  
implementing an Academic Integrity pledge designed to deepen the understanding of and  
commitment to honesty and academic integrity. The Academic Integrity Pledge states: “I am  
committed to being a person of integrity. I pledge, as a member of the Santa Clara University  
community, to abide by and uphold the standards of academic integrity contained in the Student  
Conduct Code.” The Professo

their own. Leaders of the Associated Student Government and students like you worked to create

**5.3.1 Generative AI (e.g., ChatGPT).**^4 Using AI can impede your learning to think critically,  
read with care and attention to active interpretation, and write clearly and honestly. The major  
assignments in this class challenge you to read sometimes very difficult texts with attention and  
to develop problem-solving skills that AI does not have. These assignments are intended to help  
you develop as an independent, creative interpreter rather than allowing technology (and yet  
more screen time) limit your academic capacities. AI can help you come up with new ideas and  
connections, but the writing should always belong to you, and it should remain your own work.  
You may **not us

help you come up with new ideas and  
connections, but the writing should always belong to you, and it should remain your own work.  
You may **not use AI generated text** in the following ways: (I) generating an entire text  
(or substantial portions thereof) using simple or advanced/sophisticated prompting; (ii)  
generating entire texts (or substantial portions thereof) and rewriting them for a specific purpose;  
(iii) generating single instances of short text to add to your writing. You **may use AI generate  
text** to offer tips, advice, or feedback related to your writing for this class. These permitted uses  
include: (i) asking for an outline for a writing assignment; (ii) submitting your original writing  
and asking for suggestions to improve your text. These conditions of use notwithstanding,  
AI-assistance is encouraged in all aspects of the learning process to support and amplify the  
student's own problem-solving and critical thinking and analytic writing skills.  
The accuracy of ChatGPT and other AI has become a significant concern in higher  
education, as users have found that it often produces a mix of fact and fiction, such as citing  
nonexistent quotes by

gnificant concern in higher  
education, as users have found that it often produces a mix of fact and fiction, such as citing  
nonexistent quotes by authors or imaginary research papers (even inventing a name for a journal  
of book that doesn’t exist). In other words, ChatGPT frequently makes up, in whole or in part,  
sources and references for its writing. Submitting a fake source or reference or other false  
material or using generative AI in the prohibited manners is considered academic dishonesty.  
_Consult section 5.3 above for more on the Professor’s policies regarding academic integrity._

**5.5 Recording in class or drop-in/office hours**  
The SCU Student Conduct Code expressly prohibits students from “[m]aking a video  
recording, audio recording, or streaming audio/video of private, non-public conversations and/or  
meetings, inclusive of the classroom setting, without the knowledge and consent of all recorded  
parties,” except in cases of approved disability accommodations. The Student Conduct Code also  
prohibits the “falsification or misuse, including non-authentic, altered, or fraudulent misuse, of  
University records, permits, documents, communication equipment, or identification cards and  
government issued documents.” Dissemination or sharing of any classroom recording without  
the express written permission of the instructor would be considered “misuse” and, therefore,  
prohibited by the Code. Violations of these policies may result in disciplinary action by the  
University or legal action by any aggrieved party. It is also unacceptable to copy, share, or utilize  
in any manner any portion of a Panopto recording of a class that the Professor has made  
available to you.

unacceptable to copy, share, or utilize  
in any manner any portion of a Panopto recording of a class that the Professor has made  
available to you.  
California Penal Code §632 makes it a crime to record or eavesdrop on any confidential  
communication, including a private conversation or telephone call, without the consent of all  
parties to the conversation. This statute applies to “confidential communications,” i.e.,  
conversations in which one of the parties has an objectively reasonable expectation that no one is  
listening in or overhearing the conversation. California courts have ruled that this statute applies  
to the use of hidden video cameras to record conversations as well. This statute could apply to a  
class not open to the general public in which the participants have a reasonable expectation that  
no one other than those legitimately present is listening in to the discussion.  
**5.6 Learning objectives.**  
A. Students will be able to reason ethically by drawing on major ethical theories and  
traditions, (e.g. virtue ethics, feminist ethics, deontological or consequentialist theories); by  
normatively assessing individual, professional, and institutional

. virtue ethics, feminist ethics, deontological or consequentialist theories); by  
normatively assessing individual, professional, and institutional decisions; and by articulating  
their personal engagement with the meaning of the right and the good  
B. Students will be able to analyze, critically evaluate, and apply major ethical theories  
and traditions to significant personal, professional, and institutional decisions. As part of such  
efforts, students will be able to articulate how they understand some central ethical concepts  
such as justice, happiness, the good, virtue, dignity, rights, and equality.  
C. Students will be able to demonstrate appreciation of nuance and ambiguity, as well as  
clarity and precision, in their thinking and writing about moral problems, concepts, and ideals.  
D. Students will reflect on their own ethical decisions and actions, on their roles as  
morally responsible members of the human community, and on what it means to be a good  
person.

Professor’s questions, asking questions of the Professor and other students, and by contributing  
comments and criticisms of the concepts, ideas, and arguments offered by the assigned texts,  
other students, and the instructor. Furthermore, students can and should learn from each oth

to develop is the ability to publicly articulate your understanding and analysis of a common text,  
to make an argument verbally, and to answer questions about your position and arguments.
